## Why use Brainwave

- Ready-made, modern landing UI focused on product marketing and conversion.
- Built with Vite + React for snappy local development and Tailwind CSS for easy theming.
- Includes hero, services, benefits, roadmap, pricing, and polished components with parallax/geometry accents.
- Designed to be easy to customize and ship as a marketing landing or prototype.

---

## Demo (Local)

Start a local dev server and open the app in your browser.

PowerShell (recommended on Windows):

```powershell
git clone https://github.com/your-repo/brainwave.git
Set-Location brainwave
npm install
npm run dev
```

Open http://localhost:5173 in your browser.

Notes:
- If you prefer `bash`/WSL use the same commands without `Set-Location`.
- `npm run build` produces a production bundle (`dist` folder) for static deploy.

---

## Quick Start

1. Clone the repo.
2. Install dependencies with `npm install`.
3. Run `npm run dev` and edit files under `src/`.

Common scripts (from `package.json`):

```text
npm run dev    # start development server
npm run build  # build for production
npm run preview# preview production build locally
```

---

## Project Structure (important files)

- `index.html` — app entry
- `src/main.jsx` — React bootstrap
- `src/App.jsx` — top-level components and layout
- `src/components/` — UI building blocks (Hero, Header, Footer, Roadmap, etc.)
- `src/assets/` & `public/assets/` — images and svg used across the site
- `tailwind.config.js` — design tokens and utility extensions
- `index.css` — global Tailwind layers and custom utilities

---

## Customization Tips

- Colors & tokens: edit `tailwind.config.js` under `theme.extend.colors`.
- Fonts: `index.css` imports Google fonts and defines CSS variables (`--font-sora`, etc.).
- Sections: add/remove components in `src/App.jsx` or update content in `constants/index.js`.
- Replace images: add files to `public/assets` and update imports in components.

---

## Deploying

This project builds to static files and can be hosted on Vercel, Netlify, Cloudflare Pages, or any static host.

Typical Vercel flow:

1. Push the repository to GitHub.
2. Import the repo in Vercel and set the build command to `npm run build` and publish directory to `dist`.

Netlify / GitHub Pages:
- Use `npm run build` and publish the `dist` folder.

---

